node.text:
What if I were to tell you…

That your struggle with weight loss has little to do with diet & exercise.

Well, it does.

Just not directly.

… Let me explain. 😉

Chances are, you already have a decently accurate idea of what you need to do to get results.

At the very least, you know that your current habits aren't conducive to getting the body you want.

You don't need more information. 

You need help properly implement the RIGHT information.

But before you can do that, you need to address these two areas:

Your boundaries & accountability.

~

[BOUNDARIES]

Ever heard the saying, "You can't pour from an empty cup?"

If you're always tending to everyone else's priorities, then how are you ever supposed to have time to make yourself a priority? 

I'll answer: you won't. 

That's why the first step towards building consistency with your diet & exercise plan is to make it a TOP priority in your life. 

That means planning your workouts, meals, grocery shopping, and other health-related activities first and letting everything else fit around them.

It doesn't have to be a huge time commitment either.

It can be a few workouts per week first thing in the morning before everyone else gets up or five minutes of planning your next day's meals before you shut off for the night.

Some planning > no planning.

~

[ACCOUNTABILITY]

The end goal is to have self-discipline with fitness.

But self-discipline takes time to create, and that's why accountability is so important early on in your journey.

Accountability can come in many different ways...

It can come from investing in a coach, joining a Facebook group, meeting a friend at the gym after work...

What matters is that you find a way to make your commitment bigger than yourself.

Because when the going gets tough, and you feel like quitting, you're going to need something, something, or multiple someones to keep you accountable and remind you why you're doing this in the first place.

~

What are some non-fitness struggles that have held you back from getting results? Where you able to overcome them? (If so, how?) 

Let’s get a conversation going down below. 🙂

– Carter

node.text:
Happy Sunday :)   Dropping in to share a few observation I’ve made with the habits that folks who lose weight and keep it off all share.

Even taking one or two of these five habits to heart is going to have a significantly positive impact on your fitness goals moving forward.

Let’s dive in… 

~

1️⃣ They plan ahead.

It doesn't matter how much motivation or grit or willpower or discipline or good intentions you have.

If you're not planning your meals and scheduling your workouts ahead of time, you're going to constantly feel like there's never enough time for those things.

What gets planned gets prioritized.

~

2️⃣ They eat similar foods at similar times of the day.

At first, meal planning takes time.

But once you find foods & meals that you enjoy, they can become staples in your weekly meal plan.

What and when I eat tends to be nearly identical most days — especially since having more consistency with my earlier meals allows for more flexibility for later meals.

~

3️⃣ They don't attach self-worth to their diet and exercise choices.

This might be the most important one on the list.

In fact, it's the biggest reason people struggle to stay consistent with fitness.

Truth is, you're not being "good" for eating whole foods and "bad" for eating junk foods.

You're not being “good" for working out and "bad" for skipping the gym.

All you're doing is making choices.

Some choices lead you closer to your goals; some move you further away. 

The mission is to make sure that MOST of your choices align with what you want to achieve.

~

4️⃣ They set realistic expectations and goals.

There's a fine between being ambitious and being foolish.

Losing weight takes hard work and sacrifice, but you need to be honest about how much you can realistically do given your current life situation.

It's better to do less consistently than repeatedly fail to do too much.

~

5️⃣ They never sacrifice sustainability for short-term results.

Here's a simple test to see if your approach is actually sustainable.

Ask: "Can I see myself eating and exercising this way for the rest of my life?" 

If the answer is anything but "yes," it's not worth doing. 

– Carter

node.text:
Here's the situation:

You’re out with some friends, and everybody wants to get drinks and appetizers.

Well, everyone but you.

They are only thinking about the fun.

You, on the other hand, have fitness goals you're trying to achieve.

So you get stressed.

And then you get angry about the situation.

Then you say: “eff it, I’m ordering the double bacon fries!”

And the yo-yo cycle begins...

~

Life’s gonna be chock-full of situations that make it difficult to stick to your nutrition plan.

If you want to lose weight and still maintain a normal social life, then you MUST develop skills and strategies to help you adapt. 

Here are just a few we teach at Leaner For Life:

✅ The "Work-Backwards" Method:

When you know you have a big dinner later in the day, track ahead of time (if possible) and make your earlier meals fit whatever calories remain.

(Intermittent Fasting works well in this situation too.)

✅ One Plate Rule:

When you’re in a buffet-style eating situation, see what's all available first and then fit what you want on ONE plate.

(Load half of your plate with lean protein & veggies really helps with staying full.)

✅ Indulge & Pause 

Most overeating and drinking happens mindlessly. By waiting for 10-15 minutes before getting more, you’ll have time to determine if you actually DO want more, or if you’re just bored.

✅ Never Miss Twice:

When you end up eating & drinking way more than planned (yes, it will happen), don’t get down on yourself. Instead, put your focus on getting back on track as quickly as possible.

~

Don’t let weddings, parties, dates, or dinners stress you out.

You won’t be perfect.

That’s okay.

You can still plan ahead, stay mindful, and make the best of the situation.

And even if you blow it and eat like a complete asshat...

It's OKAY. 

You don’t have to let it leak into the next meal, day, or week.

Let's use Keto as an example.

Can you lose weight quickly following the Keto diet?

If you’re consistent, then absolutely. 

Plenty of people have had success on Keto too.

But can you see yourself eating Keto for the rest of your life?

That one is up for you to decide...

I know sure as hell that I couldn’t see myself running from carbs for the rest of my life…😅

~

Folks who find themselves in a viscous yo-yo cycle with weight loss are often in that situation because they've been perpetually tricked into doing whatever will help them lose weight the fastest.

They'll follow whatever is new and flashy.

And won't put a single thought towards what that diet will look like in their life three, six, nine, or 12+ months later.

Unfortunately, they don’t usually stay consistent long enough for it to matter. 😕

~  Remember this:

Regardless of how long it takes you to lose weight, you're going to be spending the REST OF YOUR LIFE maintaining it.

So if your diet isn't teaching you how to eat for the rest of your life, It’s not worth doing.

– Carter

Something important to remember 👇

Your weight day-to-day (and even week-to-week) will fluctuate.

Not maybe.

Not likely.

It WILL fluctuate.

The good news is, what you weigh on any given day doesn’t matter a bit.

It has NOTHING to do with fat.

It could be that you ate more salt than normal…

Or that you had a bit more food than normal…
Or that you had a harder-than-normal workout…

Or it could be based on your menstrual cycle…

Again, it has NOTHING to do with gaining fat.

Because fat loss doesn’t happen overnight.

It happens slowly over the course of weeks and months.

~
The Bottom Line:

Your weight will fluctuate up and down on a regular basis.

What matters is the trend of how your weight changes over the course of weeks and months.

If your weight is trending downward over time, it’s a good sign that you’re losing fat and making progress. 💪

– Carter

As a fitness professional, my job is to help people  lose weight and improve their health through diet & exercise.

But it’s about so much more than telling people WHAT to do.

Or saying what IS and ISN’T allowed.

You need to know what to do, but also WHY you're doing it, and HOW to make it a part of your life.

If you want to lose weight & keep it off, you need to find a balance between your fitness goals & lifestyle.

Wanna know how you don’t find balance?

By trying to be 100% perfect with your nutrition and restricting anything that might be deemed “bad” or “unhealthy.”

Thing is, there’s no such thing as being 100% perfect with your nutrition.

There’s no such thing as a “bad” food either.

Hell, the same exact food can be “good” or “bad” depending on who you’re listening to…

~

Should you be eating lots of nutritious whole foods on a regular basis? (🍎🍠🥩🥗)

Absolutely.

But that doesn’t mean you can’t or shouldn’t have “less nutritious” foods. (🍷🍕🍫🍨)

What you do MOST of the time matters most.

If you’re focused on controlling your calories, getting enough protein, and eating nutritious whole foods most of the time…

Then it’s 100% okay to have the other stuff too.

~

One last thing…

If you wanna avoid certain foods because they’re overly tempting and easy to overeat, that’s totally okay.

(There are foods I keep out of my environment for the same reason.)

What matters is that YOU choose to avoid or remove them — not because some self-proclaimed health guru scared you into it.

– Carter

Feeling a bit agitated about the scale today?

GIVE ME 2-3 minutes of your time, and I promise that by the end of this caption, you’ll be much less upset about your heavier-than-normal weigh-ins.

Deal? 💪😁

So you weighed yourself this morning and saw a 2-3 pound spike from the previous day.

… And it feels like it was 2-3 pounds of pure fat. 🤬

But that’s not what happened at all!

The 2-3 pounds you see has nothing to do with fat.

It’s water you’re holding onto plus food that’s in your belly-bum that’s yet to leave your system (💩)

Stick to your plan — the thing YOU can control — and that weight will flush right out. 👌

Unfortunately, most people take a different route.

Instead of getting back on track, they’ll drastically cut calories, do “guilt” cardio, or just quit altogether.

𝗗𝗼𝗻’𝘁 𝗳𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝘁𝗿𝗮𝗽.

Your weight on a single day does NOT define your progress as a whole.

In fact, it’s normal for your weight to fluctuate up and down 2-3 pounds.

Stay focused on what YOU can control (your consistency with diet & exercise), and you will make progress.

– Carter

1. From now on, when you weigh yourself…

✅ take your weight daily (FIRST thing in the morning, AFTER using the restroom, and BEFORE eating/drinking anything).

✅ write down that data somewhere. (I use a weight tracking app)

✅ use it to see how your AVERAGE weight changes on a week-to-week & month-to-month basis.

2. If you don't wanna weigh yourself, that's totally fine.

Actions define you. Not numbers.

The goal isn’t to lose 25 pounds. 

Or 50 pounds.

Or 5 pounds. 

Or any amount of weight.

The goal is to develop the habits, lifestyle, and mindset of the version of yourself that’s leaner, fitter, and healthier.

Here’s why this is so important… 

If you go into this journey only caring about how much weight you have to lose, you’ll only ever be focused on how far you still have to go.

It’s no the mindset you wanna be in.

It’s rarely rewarding, and it usually just leads people to make unsustainable changes to their plan in hopes that it’ll speed up their results.

Plus, the truth about weight loss is that it’s just one piece of the puzzle. 

Who cares about losing 5, 25, or 50 pounds if you don’t have the habits, lifestyle, and mindset for keeping it off. 

I’m not saying it’s bad to have an outcome-based weight loss goal to lose X pounds. 

Just remember that regardless of how much weight you have to lose, you’re going to be spending the rest of your life maintaining that loss. 
 
 The diet & exercise strategies you use shouldn’t just help you lose weight — they should be helping you develop the habits, lifestyle, and mindset of the leaner, fitter, and healthier version of YOU. 

☝️THAT is the goal.

– Carter

When you’re fully invested in your fitness plan, you wanna do everything in your power to do things perfectly.

And while there’s nothing wrong with aiming for perfection, expecting it will only set you up for failure and disappointment.

Literally no one is perfect with their plan all day every day.

Not even the fittest Instagram influencers.

~

You’re going to go over your calories.

Not just once but over and over again.

What matters is how you respond.

Most people will go over their calories — even just a little — and assume the whole day’s a wash.

Instead of getting back on track, they’ll let one day of going over their calories turn into an entire weekend or week of slipping up.

If that’s you, then pay attention to this next sentence…

“𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗱𝗼 𝗺𝗼𝘀𝘁 𝗼𝗳 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝘁𝗶𝗺𝗲 𝗺𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗺𝗼𝘀𝘁.”

^That’s something I have to preach to clients (and to myself) over and over again.

Because it’s really freaking easy to forget. 😅

~

The Bottom Line: 

There are going to be moments that you slip up, stumble, and fall of track. 

What matters is how you respond.

Embrace every mistake you make not as a bad thing, but as a moment to learn, grow, and do better in the future.

When you do that, you are only ever moving forward.

What if overcoming your struggles with weight loss isn’t to do more, but less?

Hear me out...

It's easy to get stuck into thinking that more is always better.

More hours worked = more money made.
More books read = more knowledge gained.
More days practiced = more skill acquired.

More effort IN = more reward OUT.

But not everything in life follows the "more is better" formula.

Weight loss being one of them.

Yet time and time again, we fall into the "more is better" trap...

"𝘐𝘧 𝘐'𝘮 𝘯𝘰𝘵 𝘴𝘦𝘦𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘳𝘦𝘴𝘶𝘭𝘵𝘴 𝘸𝘪𝘵𝘩 𝘮𝘺 𝘤𝘶𝘳𝘳𝘦𝘯𝘵 𝘥𝘦𝘧𝘪𝘤𝘪𝘵, 𝘐 𝘫𝘶𝘴𝘵 𝘯𝘦𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘤𝘳𝘦𝘢𝘵𝘦 𝘢 𝘭𝘢𝘳𝘨𝘦𝘳 𝘥𝘦𝘧𝘪𝘤𝘪𝘵!"

"𝘐𝘧 𝘐'𝘮 𝘯𝘰𝘵 𝘮𝘢𝘬𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘱𝘳𝘰𝘨𝘳𝘦𝘴𝘴 𝘸𝘪𝘵𝘩 𝘵𝘩𝘳𝘦𝘦 𝘸𝘰𝘳𝘬𝘰𝘶𝘵𝘴 𝘱𝘦𝘳 𝘸𝘦𝘦𝘬, 𝘐 𝘨𝘶𝘦𝘴𝘴 𝘐'𝘭𝘭 𝘴𝘵𝘢𝘳𝘵 𝘨𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘦𝘷𝘦𝘳𝘺 𝘥𝘢𝘺 𝘰𝘧 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘸𝘦𝘦𝘬!"

Truth is, if you're not seeing results, It's because you're not as consistent as you need to be.

And if you want to build more consistency, it'll start with doing something a bit counter-intuitive...

I call it doing “Less, But Better.”

Instead of inconsistently doing 5-6 half-assed workouts per week, prove that you can do 2-3 kick-ass workouts consistently every week.

Instead of inconsistently tracking your calories, start simpler, like making a healthy swap at each meal.

This next part is most important…

𝗥𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗿𝗮𝗶𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗳 𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗺 𝗱𝗼𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝘂𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗹 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗰𝗮𝗻 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝘃𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝘆𝗼𝘂'𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲 𝘁𝗼 𝗱𝗼 𝗹𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗰𝗼𝗻𝘀𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗹𝘆.

Then you can add more to your plate.

Chances are, you’ll find you didn’t need to do nearly as much as you’ve thought. You just need to do enough, consistently. 💪

– Carter
⠀
PS. One cool thing about "doing enough" is that it gives you the flexibility to still live your life outside of fitness.

You can still go out to get drinks with friends because, most of the time, you're staying on top of your nutrition goals.

You can occasionally skip the gym because, MOST of the time, you're sticking to your workout schedule.

Occasionally going off track doesn’t matter because, most of the time, you’re doing enough.

If you’ve been trying to lose weight for months and haven’t seen a single budge on the scale, it’s because you’re either a) not doing enough, or b) not doing enough consistently.

Be honest...

Are you REALLY hitting your nutrition targets at least 80-90% of the time?

Are you REALLY pushing yourself as hard as you know you should during your workouts?

Or on the flip side…

Are you restricting food so much that you’re not able to stay consistent longer than a few weeks at a time?

Are you working out so hard that it’s negatively impacting your food choices and energy levels?

~

Look.

Losing weight isn’t easy.

Keeping it off isn’t easy either.

If you want to get and stay lean, you have to be willing to get uncomfortable, which often requires calling out your own bullshit.

But that’s a good thing.

Because no one ever achieved anything great without messing up a buttload of times along the way.

~
 Be ruthlessly honest with yourself.
Learn to be okay with making mistakes.
Use your mistakes to grow and improve.

You win by being the first to call yourself out and the first to do something about it.

– Carter
